Trim the root and the dark green leafy part from the @leek{1}. Halve lengthways then
thinly slice widthways. Peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2} (or use a
#garlic press{}). Finely chop the @chives{3}(finely chopped). Zest and halve the
@lemon{1/2}. Thinly slice the @red chilli{1/2}.

Bring the @water{750%ml} to the boil in a #saucepan{} and stir in the
@vegetable stock powder{2} to dissolve. Reduce the heat to low and keep the
stock on a low heat ready to add to the risotto later.

Heat a drizzle of oil in a large saucepan on medium-high heat. Once hot, add the
leek. Cook until the leek has softened, ~{4-5%minutes}. Stir occasionally.

When the leek has softened, stir in the garlic and cook for ~{1%minute}. Next,
add the @Arborio rice{175%g} and stir to evenly coat in the garlicky oil.

Once the rice has cooked for a minute, stir in a ladle of your stock. When the
stock has been absorbed by the rice, stir in another ladle of stock. Keep the pan
on medium heat and continue stirring in stock, letting it absorb each time. The
cooking time should be ~{20-25%minutes} and your risotto is done when your rice
is 'al dente' - cooked through but with a tiny bit of firmness left in the
middle.

> Add a splash of water and carry on cooking if the rice has absorbed all the
> stock but isn't quite cooked.

Once the risotto is cooked, stir in the @hot smoked salmon{150%g}(flaked) and
cook for couple of mins to ensure they are piping hot. Then remove from the
heat.

Quickly stir in the @unsalted butter{30%g}, @hard Italian style cheese{40%g}(grated)
and lemon zest until melted. Stir in half the chives and a small squeeze of
lemon juice too. Taste and add @salt{}, @pepper{} and more lemon juice too if you
feel it needs it.

Spoon the risotto into bowls and sprinkle over the remaining chives and the
sliced chilli. Grind over some black pepper and serve with any remaining lemon
chopped into wedges on the side. Enjoy!